<section id="fs-id1170903136127">
<title>Resonant Quantum Tunneling</title>
<para id="fs-id1170901840333">Quantum tunneling has numerous applications in semiconductor devices such as electronic circuit components or integrated circuits that are designed at nanoscales; hence, the term ‘<term>nanotechnology</term>.’ For example, a diode (an electric-circuit element that causes an electron current in one direction to be different from the current in the opposite direction, when the polarity of the bias voltage is reversed) can be realized by a tunneling junction between two different types of semiconducting materials. In such a <term>tunnel diode</term>, electrons tunnel through a single potential barrier at a contact between two different semiconductors. At the junction, tunneling-electron current changes nonlinearly with the applied potential difference across the junction and may rapidly decrease as the bias voltage is increased. This is unlike the Ohm’s law behavior that we are familiar with in household circuits. This kind of rapid behavior (caused by quantum tunneling) is desirable in high-speed electronic devices.</para>
<para id="fs-id1170901840342">Another kind of electronic nano-device utilizes <term>resonant tunneling</term> of electrons through potential barriers that occur in quantum dots. A <term>quantum dot</term> is a small region of a semiconductor nanocrystal that is grown, for example, in a silicon or aluminum arsenide crystal. <link target-id="CNX_UPhysics_40_06_dot"/>(a) shows a quantum dot of gallium arsenide embedded in an aluminum arsenide wafer. The quantum-dot region acts as a potential well of a finite height (shown in <link target-id="CNX_UPhysics_40_06_dot"/>(b)) that has two finite-height potential barriers at dot boundaries. Similarly, as for a quantum particle in a box (that is, an infinite potential well), lower-lying energies of a quantum particle trapped in a finite-height potential well are quantized. The difference between the box and the well potentials is that a quantum particle in a box has an infinite number of quantized energies and is trapped in the box indefinitely, whereas a quantum particle trapped in a potential well has a finite number of quantized energy levels and can tunnel through potential barriers at well boundaries to the outside of the well. Thus, a quantum dot of gallium arsenide sitting in aluminum arsenide is a potential well where low-lying energies of an electron are quantized, indicated as <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>dot</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> in part (b) in the figure. When the energy <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>electron</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> of an electron in the outside region of the dot does not match its energy <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>dot</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> that it would have in the dot, the electron does not tunnel through the region of the dot and there is no current through such a circuit element, even if it were kept at an electric voltage difference (bias). However, when this voltage bias is changed in such a way that one of the barriers is lowered, so that <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>dot</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> and <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>electron</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> become aligned, as seen in part (c) of the figure, an electron current flows through the dot. When the voltage bias is now increased, this alignment is lost and the current stops flowing. When the voltage bias is increased further, the electron tunneling becomes improbable until the bias voltage reaches a value for which the outside electron energy matches the next electron energy level in the dot. The word ‘resonance’ in the device name means that the tunneling-electron current occurs only when a selected energy level is matched by tuning an applied voltage bias, such as in the operation mechanism of the <term>resonant-tunneling diode</term> just described. Resonant-tunneling diodes are used as super-fast nano-switches.</para>
<figure id="CNX_UPhysics_40_06_dot">
<media id="fs-id1170901647662" alt="Figure a is an illustration of a tunneling diode. The quantum dot is a small region of gallium arsenide embedded in aluminum arsenide. Additional small regions of gallium arsenide are also embedded on either side of the quantum dot, separated from it by a small barrier of aluminum arsenide. The left end of the structure is attached to a negative electrode, and the right to a positive electrode. Figure b is a graph of the potential U as a function of x with no bias. The potential is constant except in two narrow regions where it has a larger constant value. The electron energy, represented by a dashed line, is between the lower and higher values of U, closer to the lower one. Two allowed energy levels, labeled as E sub dot, are shown. Both are higher than the electron energy and less than the maximum value of U. Figure c shows the potential U of x with a voltage bias across the device. The potential has the same constant value to the left of the barriers as in figure a, but decreases linearly between the barriers. U is constant again to the right of the barriers but at a lower value than before. The allowed energies are also pulled down, and the lower one now coincides with the energy of the electron.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="CNX_UPhysics_40_06_dot.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption>Resonant-tunneling diode: (a) A quantum dot of gallium arsenide embedded in aluminum arsenide. (b) Potential well consisting of two potential barriers of a quantum dot with no voltage bias. Electron energies <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>electron</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> in aluminum arsenide are not aligned with their energy levels <m:math><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>E</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>dot</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow></m:math> in the quantum dot, so electrons do not tunnel through the dot. (c) Potential well of the dot with a voltage bias across the device. A suitably tuned voltage difference distorts the well so that electron-energy levels in the dot are aligned with their energies in aluminum arsenide, causing the electrons to tunnel through the dot.</caption>
</figure>
</section>
<section id="fs-id1170901532202" class="key-concepts">
<title>Summary</title>
<list id="fs-id1170899254699" list-type="bulleted" bullet-style="bullet">
<item>A quantum particle that is incident on a potential barrier of a finite width and height may cross the barrier and appear on its other side. This phenomenon is called ‘quantum tunneling.’ It does not have a classical analog.</item>
<item>To find the probability of quantum tunneling, we assume the energy of an incident particle and solve the stationary Schrӧdinger equation to find wave functions inside and outside the barrier. The tunneling probability is a ratio of squared amplitudes of the wave past the barrier to the incident wave.</item>
<item>The tunneling probability depends on the energy of the incident particle relative to the height of the barrier and on the width of the barrier. It is strongly affected by the width of the barrier in a nonlinear, exponential way so that a small change in the barrier width causes a disproportionately large change in the transmission probability.</item>
<item>Quantum-tunneling phenomena govern radioactive nuclear decays. They are utilized in many modern technologies such as STM and nano-electronics. STM allows us to see individual atoms on metal surfaces. Electron-tunneling devices have revolutionized electronics and allow us to build fast electronic devices of miniature sizes.</item>
</list>
</section>
<section id="fs-id1170899261811" class="key-equations">
<title>Key Equations</title>
<table xmlns:data="http://www.w3.org/TR/html5/dom.html#custom-data-attribute" id="fs-id1170902869177" summary="The table has two columns and twenty rows. The first column has the names of the equations and the second column lists the equation. From left to right, the first row contains “Normalization condition in one dimension” and “P opening parenthesis x equals negative infinity, positive infinity closing parenthesis equals integral from negative infinity to positive infinity of square of absolute value of psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis dx equals 1”. The second row contains “Probability of finding a particle in a narrow interval of position in one dimension opening parenthesis x, x plus dx closing parenthesis” and “P opening parenthesis x, x plus dx closing parenthesis equals psi star opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis dx”. The third row contains “Expectation value of position in one dimension” and “expected value of x equals integral from negative infinity to positive infinity of psi star opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis dx”. The fourth row contains “Heisenberg’s position-momentum uncertainty principle” and “delta x delta p greater than equal to h bar divided by 2”. The fifth row contains “Heisenberg’s energy-time uncertainty principle” and “delta E delta t greater than equal to h bar divided by 2”. The sixth row contains “Schrӧdinger’s time-dependent equation” and “negative h bar square divided by 2 m multiplied by double partial differential of psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis with respect to x plus U opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis equals i h bar multiplied by double partial differential of psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis with respect to t”. The seventh row contains “General form of the wave function for a time-independent potential in one dimension” and “psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis equals psi opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis exponential e to the power negative i omega t”. The eighth row contains “Schrӧdinger’s time-independent equation” and “negative h bar square divided by 2 m multiplied by double partial differential of psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis with respect to x plus U opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis psi opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals E psi opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis”. The ninth row contains “Schrӧdinger’s equation (free particle)” and “negative h bar square divided by 2 m multiplied by double partial differential of psi opening parenthesis x, t closing parenthesis with respect to equals E psi opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis”. The tenth row contains “Allowed energies (particle in box of length L)” and “E subscript n equals n square numerator pi square h bar square divided by denominator 2 m L square where n equals 1, 2, 3 and so on”. The eleventh row contains “Stationary states (particle in a box of length L)” and “psi subscript n opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals square root 2 divided by L no square root sine of n pi x divided by L where n equals 1, 2, 3 and so on”. The twelfth row contains “Potential-energy function of a harmonic oscillator” and “U opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals half of m omega square x square”. The thirteenth row contains “Stationary Schrӧdinger equation” and “negative h bar square divided by 2 m multiplied by double differential of psi opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis with respect to x plus half of m omega square x square psi opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals E psi opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis”. The fourteenth row contains “The energy spectrum” and “E subscript n equals opening parenthesis n plus 1 divided by 2 closing parenthesis h bar omega where n equals 1, 2, 3 and so on”. The fifteenth row contains “The energy wave functions” and “psi subscript n opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals N subscript n exponential e to the power negative beta square x square divided by 2 multiplied by H subscript n opening parenthesis beta x closing parenthesis where n equals 0, 1, 2, 3 and so on”. The sixteenth row contains “Potential barrier” and “U opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals 0 when x is less than 0”, “U opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals U subscript 0 when x is greater than equal to 0 and less than equal to L”, “U opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis equals 0 when x is greater than L”. The seventeenth row contains Definition of the transmission coefficient” and “T opening parenthesis L, E closing parenthesis equals numerator square of absolute value of psi subscript tra opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis divided by denominator square of absolute value of psi subscript in opening parenthesis x closing parenthesis”. The eighteenth row contains “A parameter in the transmission coefficient” and “beta square equals 2 m divided by h bar square multiplied by opening parenthesis U subscript 0 minus E closing parenthesis”. The nineteenth row contains “Transmission coefficient, exact” and “T opening parenthesis L, E closing parenthesis equals numerator 1 divided by denominator square of hyperbolic cosine beta L plus opening parenthesis gamma divided by 2 closing parenthesis square multiplied by square of hyperbolic sine beta L”. The nineteenth row contains “Transmission coefficient, approximate” and “T opening parenthesis L, E closing parenthesis equals 16 E divided by U subscript 0 opening parenthesis 1 minus E divided by U subscript 0 closing parenthesis exponential e to the power negative 2 beta L”." class="unnumbered unstyled">
